Data Analysis¶

Price Analysis¶

As it can be seen from Statistical Data Exploratory, there are some outliers with the price variable. It has a min of 0 and max of 10,000. So let's get rid of the outliers. So let's get rid of these outliers.

In order to do this, I grouped the data with respect to their neighrbourhood groups and found the lower and upper limits.

Lower limit is the first quartile - 1,5 (third quartile - first quartile) Upper limit is the third quartile + 1,5 (third quartile - first quartile)

In [40]:
brooklyn = airbnb[airbnb['neighbourhood_group'] == 'Brooklyn']
manhattan = airbnb[airbnb['neighbourhood_group'] == 'Manhattan']
queens = airbnb[airbnb['neighbourhood_group'] == 'Queens']
staten = airbnb[airbnb['neighbourhood_group'] == 'Staten Island']
bronx = airbnb[airbnb['neighbourhood_group'] == 'Bronx']

price_b = brooklyn[(brooklyn['price'] > np.quantile(brooklyn['price'], 0.25) - (1.5 * iqr(brooklyn['price']))) & (brooklyn['price'] < np.quantile(brooklyn['price'], 0.75) + (1.5 * iqr(brooklyn['price'])))]
price_m = manhattan[(manhattan['price'] > np.quantile(manhattan['price'], 0.25) - (1.5 * iqr(manhattan['price']))) & (manhattan['price'] < np.quantile(manhattan['price'], 0.75) + (1.5 * iqr(manhattan['price'])))]
price_q = queens[(queens['price'] > np.quantile(queens['price'], 0.25) - (1.5 * iqr(queens['price']))) & (queens['price'] < np.quantile(queens['price'], 0.75) + (1.5 * iqr(queens['price'])))]
price_s = staten[(staten['price'] > np.quantile(staten['price'], 0.25) - (1.5 * iqr(staten['price']))) & (staten['price'] < np.quantile(staten['price'], 0.75) + (1.5 * iqr(staten['price'])))]
price_br = bronx[(bronx['price'] > np.quantile(bronx['price'], 0.25) - (1.5 * iqr(bronx['price']))) & (bronx['price'] < np.quantile(bronx['price'], 0.75) + (1.5 * iqr(bronx['price'])))]

price = pd.concat([price_b, price_m, price_q, price_s, price_br], axis = 0)

We can see that the average prices in Manhattan is more than Brooklyn. And the prices in Brooklyn is more than Queens, Staten Island or Bronx. However there is no any superiority between Queens, Staten Island and Bronx.

Linear Regression¶

Let's try to find some relations between variables. We have some non-numeric variables in data. So in order to use these variables, we have to represent them as numeric variables. For this purpose, I will use preprocessing in sklearn library. I have used neighbourhood_group, neighbourhood and roomtype variables and converted them into numeric representives. I defined some dummy variables and called them 'Temp...'.

In [46]:
reg = pd.get_dummies(price, prefix=['Temp_Neighbourhood', 'Temp_Room_Type'], columns=['neighbourhood_group','room_type'])

Let's seperate our data into two parts: train, test. We will split the data into %80 train and %20 test.

In [49]:
lm = LinearRegression()

X = reg.drop(['price', 'id', 'name', 'host_id', 'host_name', 'neighbourhood', 'latitude', 'longitude', 'last_review'], inplace=False, axis=1)
y = reg['price']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=10)

lm.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions = lm.predict(X_test)

Let's have a look how close our predictions to the real values.

In [50]:
accuracy_score(y_test, predictions.round(), normalize=False)
Out[50]:
69

Let's see our R-squared value to see the performance of overall predictive equation.

In [51]:

number_of_reviews and reviews_per_month have a correlation of 0.6. This shows that %60 of the number_of_reviews can be described with reviews_per_month. So we can try to remove it from the equation and re-try the regression model to see if there is any improvement in regression results. In the model below, I took the reviews_per_month variable out of the equation to see if we can get any better solution.

In [54]:
lm = LinearRegression()

X = reg.drop(['price', 'id', 'name', 'host_id', 'host_name', 'neighbourhood', 'latitude', 'longitude', 'last_review', 'reviews_per_month'], inplace=False, axis=1)
y = reg['price']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=10)

lm.fit(X_train, y_train)

predictions = lm.predict(X_test)
